Descirptions of variables :

The Regressor variables (X) are as follows:

1] Transaction.date(Nominal) - the year in which the transaction was made (integer)

2] House.age(Ordinal) - Age of the house (double)

3] Distance.to.the.nearest.MRT.station(Ordinal) - distance between the house and nearest metro station (double)

4] Number.of.convenience.stores(Ordinal) - Number of the convenience stores around the house (double)

5] Latitude(Nominal) - Latitudinal co-ordinate of the house (double)

6] Longitude(Nominal) - Longitudinal co-ordinate of the house (double)

The Response variabe is (Y):

House.price.of.unit.area(Ordinal) - Price of per unit area of the house (Double)’

Outlier detection

par(mfrow = c(2,3))
boxplot(df$House.age, main = 'House Age', col= '#FF671F')
boxplot(df$Distance.to.the.nearest.MRT.station, main = "Distance to the nearest Metro station", col= 'white')
boxplot(df$Number.of.convenience.stores, main = 'Number of convenience stores', col='#046A38')
boxplot(df$Latitude, main = 'Latitude', col= 'lightblue')
boxplot(df$Longitude, main = 'Longitude', col= 'lightblue')

After examining the boxplots of each column, it can be observed that there are many outliers that cannot be simply removed from the dataset. Therefore, a data cleaning technique called “winsorizing” needs to be applied to address these outliers.

Winsorizing is a statistical method used to handle outliers. It involves replacing the values that exceed the extreme value thresholds with the limit values. These extreme values are identified by calculating a certain percentile of the data.For eg To provide an illustration,

applying a 90% winsorization to a dataset would imply that any data point that lies outside the 5th and 95th percentiles of the distribution will be replaced with the values of the 5th and 95th percentile data points, correspondingly.

par(mfrow = c(1,3))
df[1:6]<-lapply(df[1:6], Winsorize)
boxplot(df$Distance.to.the.nearest.MRT.station, main = "Distance to the nearest Metro station", col='#FF8000')
boxplot(df$Latitude, main = 'Latitude', col='#FF8000')
boxplot(df$Longitude, main = 'Longitude', col='#FF8000')

since we still see outliers in 2 columns, we transform the variables into log

df$Distance.to.the.nearest.MRT.station = log(df$Distance.to.the.nearest.MRT.station)
df$Longitude = log(df$Longitude)

par(mfrow = c(1,2))
boxplot(df$Distance.to.the.nearest.MRT.station, main = "Distance to the nearest Metro station", col='lightgreen')
boxplot(df$Longitude, main = 'Longitude', col='lightgreen')

We note that Outliers still remain in the Longitude column when we convert to log

So we drop the outliers rows from the dataset

par(mfrow = c(1,1))
new_data = subset(df, df$Longitude>boxplot(df$Longitude, plot= 'False')$stats[1,])
boxplot(new_data$Longitude, main="Longitude")

After dropping we see that the outliers increased. So we just use the previous plot without removing the outliers as there are only 3 outlying points

Assumptions

Assumption 1:

Linear relationship between dependent and independent variables. Checking this assumption by plotting each dependent variable against dependent variable in a scatter plot.

par(mfrow = c(2,3))
plot(House.price.of.unit.area ~ Transaction.date,data=df)
plot(House.price.of.unit.area ~ House.age,data=df)
plot(House.price.of.unit.area ~ Distance.to.the.nearest.MRT.station,data=df)
plot(House.price.of.unit.area ~ Number.of.convenience.stores,data=df)
plot(House.price.of.unit.area ~ Latitude,data=df)
plot(House.price.of.unit.area ~ Longitude,data=df)

We see that:

Transaction date does not have a linear relationship with house price

House age is pretty scattered and no significant relationship can be seen between the independent and dependent variables

Distance to the nearest metro station has a negative linear relationship with house price meaning that the price of the house increases the closer it is to a metro station

Number of convenience stores has a positive linear relationship with house price meaning the price increases with the increase in number of stores in its vacinity

Longitude and Latitude also have a significant effect on the price of the house

#VIF

df.lm<-lm(House.price.of.unit.area ~Distance.to.the.nearest.MRT.station+Number.of.convenience.stores+Latitude+Longitude,data=df)

Checking multicollinearity We use the VIF test to check for multicollinearity

VIF(df.lm)[VIF(df.lm)>5]
## named numeric(0)

Assumption 3:

Variance of residuals is constant.

We use the plot of standardized residuals against predicted values to check for the variance

par(mfrow=c(2,2))
plot(df.lm)

here we see that the variance of observations is constant

Assumption 4:

Independence of Observations

The Durbin-Watson Statistic shows the autocorrelation between observations

It ranges from 0 to 4.

0-2 indicates a positive autocorrelation

2 indicates no autocorrelation

2-4 indicates a negative autocorrelation

dwtest(df.lm)
## 
##  Durbin-Watson test
## 
## data:  df.lm
## DW = 2.1437, p-value = 0.9293
## alternative hypothesis: true autocorrelation is greater than 0

Since the DW statistic is close to 2 and the p-value is higher than 0.05, we fail to reject the null hypothesis that there is no autocorrelation between the observations

Thus proving that there is no multicollinearity and the observations are independent.

Multivariate normality

Adjusted R-squared is a statistical measure that accounts for the number of independent variables in a linear regression model and provides an adjusted estimate of the proportion of the variance in the dependent variable that is explained by the model. #Adjusted R^2 is 0.6027 Which means, our model explains the variables with 60.27% accuracy
